          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In the clinical scenario described, the motorcyclist's arm hangs at his side in </p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In the clinical scenario described, the motorcyclist's arm hangs at his side in the 'waiter's tip position' — shoulder adducted, elbow extended, forearm pronated. This deformity results from injury to which structures?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Accessory nerve (cranial nerve XI)</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>CN XI supplies the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius. Its injury causes shoulder drop and weakness of head turning, not the waiter's tip limb deformity.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Upper roots of the brachial plexus (C5–C6)</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Tearing of C5 and C6 roots denervates the deltoid, biceps, and supinator, causing the arm to adduct, internally rotate, and extend — the classic waiter's tip position of Erb's palsy.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Lower trunk of the brachial plexus (C8–T1)</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Lower trunk injury causes Klumpke's palsy with loss of intrinsic hand muscles and claw hand, not the waiter's tip position seen here.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Cervical sympathetic chain</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Sympathetic chain damage produces Horner's syndrome (ptosis, miosis, anhidrosis), not a limb position deformity.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The waiter's tip position results from C5–C6 root injury (Erb's palsy). These roots supply the deltoid and biceps; when lost, the arm hangs adducted, internally rotated, with the elbow extended."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. The waiter's tip position is the hallmark of Erb's palsy — an upper brachial plexus injury at C5–C6 that paralyses the deltoid, biceps, brachialis, and supinator."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
