          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>When the sternocleidomastoid contracts on one side, it tilts the head toward the</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>When the sternocleidomastoid contracts on one side, it tilts the head toward the same side. What happens to the chin?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>It rotates toward the same side</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The SCM's oblique attachment from the sternum and clavicle to the mastoid process pulls the chin in the opposite direction, not toward the contracting side.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It remains in the midline</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Unilateral SCM contraction produces both tilt and rotation simultaneously. The chin does not stay central — this combination is exactly what produces the torticollis head position.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It rotates toward the opposite side</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The SCM runs from the sternum and medial clavicle to the mastoid process. Unilateral contraction tilts the head ipsilaterally while rotating the chin contralaterally — the head position seen in torticollis.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It extends backward toward the occiput</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Neck extension is produced by the posterior cervical muscles. In fact, bilateral SCM contraction does the opposite — it flexes the neck, drawing the chin toward the sternum.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The SCM tilts the head ipsilaterally and rotates the chin contralaterally. Understanding this dual action explains why torticollis presents with the head tilted to one side and the chin pointing to the other."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. Unilateral SCM contraction tilts the head to the same side and rotates the chin to the opposite side. This is exactly the deformity seen in congenital muscular torticollis."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
