          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A pituitary tumour grows upward and compresses the optic chiasm from below. Whic</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A pituitary tumour grows upward and compresses the optic chiasm from below. Which fibres are damaged first, and what visual field defect results?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Uncrossed temporal retinal fibres — loss of both nasal visual fields</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Temporal retinal fibres remain on the same side and lie laterally in the chiasm. They are not the first fibres compressed by a centrally expanding pituitary tumour.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>All fibres of one optic nerve — complete monocular blindness</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A pituitary tumour compresses the chiasm, not a single optic nerve. Optic nerve lesions cause monocular blindness, but that is a different localisation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Crossing nasal retinal fibres — loss of both temporal visual fields</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Nasal retinal fibres, which carry information from the temporal (outer) visual fields, cross at the centre of the chiasm. A pituitary tumour growing upward compresses these crossing fibres first, producing bitemporal hemianopia — the 'tunnel vision' pattern.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Crossing nasal retinal fibres — loss of both nasal visual fields</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>While nasal retinal fibres do indeed cross at the chiasm, they carry information from the temporal visual fields, not the nasal fields. Losing these fibres means losing the outer fields, not the inner ones.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Nasal retinal fibres cross at the chiasm and carry temporal (outer) field information. A pituitary tumour compressing the chiasm from below damages these crossing fibres, producing bitemporal hemianopia — loss of both outer visual fields."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct. The crossing nasal retinal fibres at the chiasm carry temporal field information. A pituitary tumour compressing from below selectively damages these fibres, causing bitemporal hemianopia."
                }
              ],
